  urldate = {2024-06-14},
  abstract = {Approximate nearest neighbor (ANN) search plays a vital role in the database system, data retrieval, and any scenario where similar elements need to be queried in a fast manner. The traditional ANN tasks are typically completed by hash-style techniques, such as the locality-sensitive-hash (LSH). However, while the amount of data is consistently rising in modern real applications, an ANN system is required to scale to the larger data size as well as the increasing data dimension. Considering that the hash functions struggle with precision and efficiency on such a dataset, the hash-based ANN systems are becoming unsuitable for big data environments. By contrast, the learning-based methods provide a promising way for handling high-dimensional data, which also reach a good balance between precision and efficiency in ANN tasks. Starting from this, we advocate that a pleasing way to improve the ANN system is to leverage both the deep learning and the distribution information. We propose a practical deep learning-based hash framework, which is termed as deep learning-based locality-sensitive-hash (DeepLSH). This framework optimizes the binary hash code by building up an encoder-decoder deep neural network which can be trained in an end-to-end manner. Experimental results show that our method satisfies the generalized LSH and outperforms the existing hashing algorithms on challenging datasets.},
